The world born on September 11th
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th anniversary of the September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks in the United States.
That day, 19 terrorists took control of four civilian airplanes, hijacked two of the planes and flew them into the World Trade Center towers in New York, struck the Pentagon with a third, and then crashed a fourth plane in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, which many believe was the White House or another U.S. government building in Washington, D.C.
All the air pirates were from the Middle East, and 15 of them were from Saudi Arabia.
All had been trained in Afghanistan, and four in American flight schools, as part of a planned, organized, and executed operation by Al-Qaïda (the "base"), the terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
By the end of the day, we mourned the deaths of 2,977 innocent men, women, and children, and over 6,000 injured.
Most of them were American, although citizens from more than a hundred other countries also lost their lives.
Many at the time feared that September 11 had ushered in an era defined by global terrorism.
Indeed, other attacks carried out by Al-Qaeda followed, including several bombings on Madrid's trains in March 2004, and the attack carried out on London's public transport in July 2005.
Terrorists who pledged allegiance to the Islamic State (IS) also killed 32 people at Brussels Airport in March 2016, and carried out a series of smaller attacks (often by using vehicles to run over pedestrians).
However, neither the United States nor any of their allies have ever suffered an attack of comparable magnitude to those of September 11th – which are in a different category altogether.
It is therefore worth asking: Beyond the immediate losses, what difference did September 11th make?
Has history changed, and if so, to what extent?
Many reasons explain why the terrorists were not able to carry out any other major attacks.
After the American invasion of Afghanistan, Al-Qaeda lost its sanctuary.
Almost all governments around the world have established screening procedures that make it more difficult for potential terrorists to access airports and airplanes.
States have significantly strengthened their intelligence, police, and military capabilities in order to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation; terrorism is one of the few areas in which states often at odds are willing and ready to work together to a significant extent.
There is also now a broad consensus on what constitutes terrorism—the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians for political purposes—as well as a degree of support for the principle that governments should not distinguish between terrorists and those who provide them with sanctuary and support.
The time when individuals and groups willing to kill in the name of their cause were romanticized as fighters for freedom is over.
It is not a matter of claiming that terrorism has ceased to reap several tens of thousands of lives each year.
Nevertheless, almost all attacks take place in the Middle East, Africa, and South Asia within the context of ongoing conflicts (mainly in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Libya, Somalia, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Yemen), as opposed to isolated attacks of the September 11 type against major powers.
Terrorism is becoming increasingly localized and decentralized.
It is also resilient: the capture of a terrorist organization leader does not necessarily mean the end of the group.
Al-Qaeda, for example, survived the elimination of Bin Laden by U.S. special forces in Pakistan, nearly ten years after the September 11 attacks.
It is therefore not surprising that terrorism persists, with no solution to the problem on the horizon.
The possibility of a new 9/11 cannot be ruled out either, although the U.S. government has recently stated that the "most urgent terrorist threat" to the country exists domestically.
As the Provisional Irish Republican Army formulated after its failed 1984 attempt to assassinate British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, "Today, we haven't had luck, but remember that it only takes one chance."
You will always need to have it.
The danger lies in the fact that one day, terrorists may acquire nuclear material, or manage to develop and use a biological or chemical weapon, in which case terrorism could determine the era.
At the moment, that is not the case.
September 11 marked a historic turning point, with a profound impact on American foreign policy over the past two decades.
Although the attacks did not lead to a global era of terrorism, they certainly gave rise to the famous global war on terror, with major consequences for the behavior of the United States around the world, the image of America in the eyes of the world, and the way in which many Americans came to view their country's foreign policy.
The saga began in Afghanistan.
Shortly after the September 11 attacks, the United States presented the Taliban with a choice, as they then controlled the Afghan government: hand over the Al-Qaïda leaders who were about to leave the country and were responsible for organizing the September 11 attacks, or risk their rule.
After the Taliban refused to hand over Al-Qaeda leaders, U.S. intelligence and military personnel collaborated with an loosely structured Afghan tribal confederation known as the Northern Alliance to overthrow the Taliban.
The United States contributed to the formation of a successor government that took control of most of the country.
This control has never been absolute, nor uncontested.
Many individuals loyal to the Taliban and Al-Qaïda have taken refuge in the neighboring Pakistan, where they have gradually regained their strength and resumed their military operations against the government that had replaced them.
On the other hand, the United States have not done enough to build an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deprive the Taliban of sanctuaries in Pakistan.
Instead, the United States strengthened its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, becoming essentially a partner of the government in its civil war.
At its peak, the United States' intervention in Afghanistan mobilized more than 100,000 American soldiers.
Over more than twenty years, the cost of operations amounts to more than 2,000 billion dollars, for the loss of more than 2,300 American lives, and several tens of thousands among the Afghans.
The effort was both excessive and insufficient.
The American presence has deprived the Afghan government of much of its legitimacy and sparked opposition to the United States, while the Taliban proved more persistent than the Americans, who in 2020 had lost all willingness to fight in a conflict destined to end only in an endless stalemate.
The global war on terrorism also led the United States to go to war in Iraq.
The question remains open as to whether President George W. Bush would have acted militarily had September 11th not occurred.
The attacks certainly reinforced his tendency to signal to the world that the United States was not, as President Richard Nixon had phrased during the Vietnam War, a "helpless and pitiful giant."
This led some members of the administration (notably Vice President Dick Cheney) to reject the risk of terrorists acquiring weapons of mass destruction, which Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein appeared to possess (which, according to most participants, was not the case).
Others sought to spread democracy in Iraq, and then throughout the entire Middle East, believing that this approach was not only feasible but would also make the region far less likely to produce and support terrorists.
Triggered in March 2003, the war in Iraq did not unfold as the Bush administration, along with numerous members of Congress (including Joe Biden, then a senator), and global leaders who had approved it, had hoped or anticipated.
The United States were not prepared for most of the events to come.
The military victories achieved initially certainly allowed the government to be ousted, but quickly gave way to widespread unrest as well as a violent civil war.
The decision to dissolve the Iraqi army and exclude many Iraqis associated with the previous regime from government positions worsened an already chaotic situation.
More fundamentally, Iraq, like Afghanistan, has shown the limits of what military force can achieve at a cost and within reasonable timeframes.
In the end, the United States were forced to strengthen their military presence, increasing it to nearly 170,000 troops, in order to protect the besieged successor government in Baghdad.
A certain degree of stability has been achieved, but at a considerable cost.
The United States spent at least as much in Iraq as in Afghanistan, but for a far heavier human toll: over 4,000 American soldiers killed, a far greater number of wounded, and an exploding rate of suicides among American troops (both in Iraq and Afghanistan).
This total also excludes deaths among private contractors and Iraqis, for whom estimates vary widely, but whose number is certainly in the hundreds of thousands.
The war in Iraq also weakened the United States in other ways.
No evidence has ever demonstrated Iraq's involvement in the September 11 attacks, and America's reputation suffered when the argument for a military intervention without UN approval—aimed at eliminating Saddam's weapons of mass destruction—proved to be based on no real foundation.
Images of American soldiers abusing Iraqi prisoners have further tarnished the country's reputation.
Furthermore, an Iraq at war with itself has become synonymous with an emerging Iran as the most powerful country in the region (or one of the two most powerful, if Israel is taken into account).
Since the war, Iran has strengthened its influence over Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Lebanon.
Iraq and Afghanistan have also proven to be two major strategic distractions.
While the United States became deeply involved in the Middle East and South Asia, regions lacking major powers and economic dynamism, the geopolitical balance shifted against the United States, both in Europe and in East Asia, due to the emergence of a more aggressive Russia and a stronger, more assertive China.
The global war against terrorism could not and has not provided the United States with a compass for their approach to foreign policy regarding a renewed rivalry among major powers.
The wars fought following September 11 also led to significant domestic consequences for the United States.
They shook the confidence in a country that had emerged from the Cold War strong with a historically unprecedented dominant power, and undermined the national unity that had surfaced immediately after the attacks.
The costs and failures associated with these wars have also fueled opposition to a major and lasting global role for the United States, giving rise to a new trend of isolationism.
Similarly, this bellicose tendency, associated with the global financial crisis of 2007-2009 and its economic repercussions, severely impacted Americans' confidence in elites, thus stimulating the rise of a populist sentiment that, among other consequences, contributed to Donald Trump's rise to power.
Today's America is more divided than ever internally, and increasingly unwilling to pursue this form of active foreign policy that characterized it since the end of World War II, and which has largely benefited Americans as well as many others.
Looking back, we can now see September 11 as a harbinger of what was to come: not the globalization of terrorism, but the terrors of globalization.
The attacks sent the message that distance and borders mattered little in the global era.
Nothing remains local for very long anymore, whether it be terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis originating from poor American financial management.
We are all currently facing a pandemic virus that has killed several million people since its emergence in China in December 2019.
The fires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves devastating many regions of the world are the result of climate change, itself a cumulative effect of human activity that releases unsustainable amounts of heat-trapping greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.
The era initiated by recent events is concluding a cycle, marking the 20th anniversary of the American intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were quickly expelled from power; in recent weeks, they have regained it just as easily.
It is too early to know whether the Taliban will resume their old habits by once again becoming a terrorist sanctuary, and whether terrorists around the world will take pride in their victory over America and its allies.
What we do know, on the other hand, is that terrorism remains a feature of our world.
He will not define the future, but will remain one of the visible aspects of a globalization that already determines it.
